04770nam a22005775i 9780226586571DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20232023ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2022023735  a9780226586571  a(DE-B1597)642290  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aBJ1535.R45bS36 2023 4aBJ1535.R45bS36 2023 7aLAN0000002bisacsh04a179/.8223/eng/202206291 aSchneider, Robert A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Return of Resentment :bThe Rise and Decline and Rise Again of a Political Emotion /cRobert A. Schneider. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Life of Ideas00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1: Sensible Resentment in the Age of Sensibility: The Eighteenth Century -- t2: Contentious Resentment: Acting Out Resentment in the Early Modern Past -- t3: A Specter Is Haunting Europe: The Specter of a Resentful “People” -- t4: The Nietzschean Moment -- t5: The Rise and Decline of the “Resentment Paradigm” -- t6: The Uses of Resentment -- t7: The Two Sixties and Resentment: One Without, the Other With -- t8: The Return of Resentment: Anatomizing a Contemporary Political Emotion -- tConclusion: Thinking about Resentment Today -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCharts the long history of resentment, from its emergence to its establishment as the word of the moment. The term “resentment,” often casually paired with words like “hatred,” “rage,” and “fear,” has dominated US news analysis since November 2016. Despite its increased use, this word seems to defy easy categorization. Does “resentment” describe many interlocking sentiments, or is it just another way of saying “anger”? Does it suggest an irrational grievance, as opposed to a legitimate callout of injustice? Does it imply political leanings, or is it nonpartisan by nature? In The Return of Resentment, Robert A. Schneider explores these questions and more, moving from eighteenth-century Britain to the aftermath of the French Revolution to social movements throughout the twentieth century. Drawing on a wide range of writers, thinkers, and historical experiences, Schneider illustrates how resentment has morphed across time, coming to express a collective sentiment felt by people and movements across the political spectrum. In this history, we discover resentment’s modernity and its ambiguity—how it can be used to dismiss legitimate critique and explain away violence, but also convey a moral stance that demands recognition. Schneider anatomizes the many ways resentment has been used to label present-day movements, from followers of Trump and supporters of Brexit to radical Islamicists and proponents of identity politics. Addressing our contemporary political situation in a novel way, The Return of Resentment challenges us to think critically about the roles different emotions play in politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aPolitical psychologyzEuropexHistory. 0aPolitical psychologyzUnited States. 0aResentmentxPolitical aspectszEurope. 0aResentmentxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aResentmentzEuropexHistory. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh  aresentment, Donald Trump, Brexit, Friedrich Nietzsche, Populism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079732940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226586571423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226586571/original  a97